hints_latex:
Recall the definition of a derivative at a point $x=a$ is

\begin{align*}
f'(a)=\lim_{x\to{}a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}
\end{align*}

if the limit exists. What must be true for the limit to exist in terms
of sided limits?

sols_latex:
A function $f(x)$ is differentiable at the point $x=2$ if the following
limit exists

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \to 2}\frac{f(x)-f(2)}{x-2}
\end{align*}

Equivalently, $f(x)$ is differentiable at the point $x=2$ if the
following limit exists

\begin{align*}
\lim_{h \to 0}\frac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h}
\end{align*}
